The facility is also supposed to identify an alternative release scenario that is more likely to occur than the worst-case scenario, but still result in an off-site toxic endpoint.  The plant utilized a scenario involving the rupture of 5/16 inch tubing releasing chlorine gas at a rate of 15 pounds per minute.  Assuming that the chlorine scrubber unit would mitigate one ton of gas the plant determined the alternative release scenario would have no off-site consequences.



D) The Boyd Lake WTP Accidental Release Prevention Program is based on the following elements:



Advanced process and safety equipment;

A chlorine gas detector in the chlorine room that triggers audible alarms and a chlorine scrubber system at concentrations greater than 3 parts per million. The alarms consists of a local alarm on the detector, the plant SCADA computer system and a beacon and klaxon horn on the scrubber;

A sprinkler system to cool the chlorine containers in the event of a fire;

Standardized operating procedures;

Training of operators and maintenance personnel in the chlorine process;

Preventive maintenance program for chlorine process equipment and safety equipment;

Periodic hazard review of chlorine process equipment and procedures;

Auditing and inspection program;

Investigation program (which will investigate future incidents that could reasonably result in a chlorine release); and

Personal protective equipment, including breathing apparatus for routine container changeouts.



